===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|mathematics|computer graphics}} A type of [[parametric]] curve defined by a set of [[control point]]s, two of which are the ends of the curve, while the others determine its shape. {{defdate|From 1960s.}}
#: {{ux|en|'''Bézier curves''' are applied, for example in [[computer graphics]] and [[animation]], to produce smooth, infinitely scalable curves.}}
#: {{syn|en|bezier}}
#* '''2003''', {{w|Samuel Buss|Samuel R. Buss}}, ''3D Computer Graphics: A Mathematical Introduction with OpenGL'', {{w|Cambridge University Press}}, [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=LBm1khtUX0cC&pg=PA163&dq=%22B%C3%A9zier+curve%22%7C%22B%C3%A9zier+curves%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiPvu-Y3fPyAhUWq5UCHW6WDBAQ6AF6BAghEAI#v=onepage&q=%22B%C3%A9zier%20curve%22%7C%22B%C3%A9zier%20curves%22&f=false page 163],
#*: So, instead, it is often better to combine multiple '''Bézier curves''' to form a longer, more complicated curve called a ''piecewise '''Bézier curve'''''.
#*: This section discusses how to join '''Bézier curves''' together – especially how to join them so as to preserve continuity and smoothness (i.e., continuity of the first derivative).
#* '''2008''', T. Theoharis, G. Papaioannou, N. Platis, N. M. Patrikalakis, ''Graphics & Visualization: Principles and Algorithms'', Taylor & Francis (A K Peters / CRC Press), [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=9UwhIdwmS9cC&pg=PA193&dq=%22B%C3%A9zier+curve%22%7C%22B%C3%A9zier+curves%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiPvu-Y3fPyAhUWq5UCHW6WDBAQ6AF6BAhTEAI#v=onepage&q=%22B%C3%A9zier%20curve%22%7C%22B%C3%A9zier%20curves%22&f=false page 193],
